1040;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="2586" y="1626" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+4+7+8+10]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   198k lives-eq/$1k · 61% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 39%&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + climate_tipping_points + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 4 climate_tipping_points → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 suffering_focused → 10 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJylWG1T20gS%2Fitd1O2dnTNGkt%2FNcVUEzC4VSChCLrUVUs5YGtuzSDO6mRHGybK%2F%2FXpmJFsGUyjnD0kJa%2Frpp1%2BnWz%2F2IjolWaxPRET3hnsHB3B0dAQ3kjAOWkAoyfclPiw43GaB57dhIWQc3TO6gIU%2FDsbtcW%2FcH%2Fse1JQWKfhe3QDccgQ6VipLUs0Eh3COeEPwICVShHNGYgPnDwLwYUrkmCzIcjzPEsJV8SIAwllCYjVWIqGLOdHFmzaEMb7RdKxZmjI%2BG6eCcb2S7K0k8ZCmiD6OxUq6DyqbTqk0clMRZopGKy4ecKrHnM6IZvd07GDGMT4ra9GIhHMga7OYAgJXSz3H5ymLKaDT1q%2FVAWhDm0SRaoCk6GnGqQIhLZik%2B%2BgNklCkyBT%2BrufUOeofCqYZDy3GIYQiSYVCuusDKMsjioj4E3PUlCY8IrHgFBIMZdyEb6tIje6%2FG