in%2BQX01fmW3ccPpV9KH367ut%2FetqP0AjPX9Cz%2FXIrXOEMW5vNd4eMrSjA7itIn%2FOjl%2Fx6M5nE%3D" id="w1_2_4_7_9"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#eeb3b3;strokeColor=#c0392b;fontColor=#5a1410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="1030" y="1084" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+4+7+9+10]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   64k lives-eq/$1k · 61% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 39%&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + climate_tipping_points + animals_matter_a_lot + meat_eater_problem + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 4 climate_tipping_points → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 9 meat_eater_problem → 10 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJylWG1v27YW%2FisHwXavnWs7kvzu3gxIE2cLmrRBmqIY6sKlJdrmIpEaScVxu%2By375CSbDnWEAH%2BkEQRyec855Xn6MdRQOckCfW5COjR6OjkBE5PT%2BFeEsZBC%2FAl%2Bb7GhxWHSeI5bgdWQobBI6MrWLlTb9qZ9qfDqetATWkRg%2BvUDcCEI9CZUkkUayY4%2BEvEG4EDMZHCXzISGjh36IELcyKnZEXW02USEa7yBQ8IZxEJ1VSJiK6WROcrHfBDXNF0qlkcM